[?2004lthres[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> Executive Recommendation
[?2004l[?2004h> ------------------------
[?2004ld [?2004h> We recommend that the XGBoost fraud detection model (v4.2.1) be DEPLOYED with a TUNED classification threshold of 0.644, rather than deployed as-is (with the analyst's default threshold of 0.5) or rejected. This recommendation is based on a rigorous cost-benefit optimization that balances the high cost of undetected fraud against the manual investigation capacity of our fraud operations team.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> Recommended Classification Threshold
[?2004l[?2004h> ------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> We recommend setting the decision threshold to exactly 0.644. 
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> Why this threshold?
[?2004l[?2004h> - Operational Feasibility: Our manual investigation team of 12 analysts has a hard capacity limit of 1,500 alerts/day. At a threshold of 0.644, the model flags approximately 1,480.3 alerts per day. This represents a 98.7% capacity utilization rate, meaning the team can handle the volume without any additional headcount or backlog buildup.
[?2004l[?2004h> - Cost-Benefit Optimization: Under the constraint that daily alerts must not exceed 1,500, a threshold of 0.644 is the mathematically optimal choice. It minimizes the total quarterly cost to $192.73M. Lower thresholds would generate a volume of alerts that our team cannot review, while higher thresholds would let too many high-loss fraud cases go undetected.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> Expected Financial Impact (Per Quarter)
[?2004l[?2004h> ---------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> Based on Finance-validated cost parameters ($4,200 loss per undetected fraud case, $35 cost per manual investigation) and our quarterly transaction volume of 2,800,000, we have modeled the financial outcomes for different operational scenarios:
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> 1. Baseline Scenario: No Model Deployed (Flag Nothing)
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Description: All fraud cases pass through undetected. We incur no manual investigation costs but suffer full fraud losses.
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Fraud Loss: $448,110,562.69
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Investigation Cost: $0.00
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Total Quarterly Cost: $448,110,562.69
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> 2. Feasible Deployment Scenario: Tuned Model (Threshold = 0.644)
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Description: The model is deployed with the recommended threshold. Daily alerts are capped within team capacity.
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Fraud Loss (Undetected Fraud): $188,067,127.34  (representing 44,778 undetected fraud cases)
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Investigation Cost: $4,662,981.24  (representing 133,228 investigations)
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Total Quarterly Cost: $192,730,108.59
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Net Quarterly Savings vs. Baseline: $255,380,454.10
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> 3. Analyst Draft Scenario: Unfeasible Model (Threshold = 0.5)
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Description: This is the default threshold recommended by the analyst. It is operationally impossible because it flags 4,287.4 alerts per day (285.8% of team capacity).
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Fraud Loss (Undetected Fraud): $113,769,002.96
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Investigation Cost: $13,505,231.98  (assuming all could be investigated)
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Total Quarterly Cost: $127,274,234.95
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Note: Because our team capacity is capped at 1,500 alerts/day, we would actually not be able to achieve these savings. The unreviewed alerts would overflow, leading to unmitigated fraud and a breakdown of fraud operations.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> Daily Operational Volume and Capacity Fit
[?2004l[?2004h> -----------------------------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> At the recommended threshold of 0.644:
[?2004l[?2004h> - Daily Transaction Volume: 31,111.11 transactions/day
[?2004l[?2004h> - Daily Flagged Transactions (Alerts): 1,480.3 alerts/day (an alert rate of 4.76% of transactions)
[?2004l[?2004h> - Capacity Capacity Margin: 19.7 alerts/day remaining before reaching the 1,500 limit.
[?2004l[?2004h> - Capacity Status: FITS. No additional hiring or overtime is required. The team will operate at maximum efficiency, blocking a substantial amount of fraud while keeping the workload manageable.
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> Strategic Next Steps
[?2004l[?2004h> --------------------
[?2004l[?2004h> 1. Fix Upstream Scoring Pipeline: Prioritize an engineering ticket to investigate why 585 out-of-bounds records (including 500 duplicates) were included in the raw export. Ensure the scoring pipeline does not re-score or append duplicate records in production.
[?2004l[?2004h> 2. Implement Dynamic Thresholding: As fraud operations capacity grows (e.g., if we hire more analysts) or if we implement automation tools that lower the cost of investigation below $35, we can lower the threshold (down towards 0.29) to capture more fraud and unlock additional millions of dollars in savings.
[?2004l[?2004h> """
[?2004l[?2004h> 
